author: @mikekane2492
text:
The journalist was doing a good job and asking the right questions, especially when she sensed the man was in distress. 

There's countless recorded incidents in unregulated therapies where the distress is reinterpreted and rationalised as "healing", just as the Shaman did here. In a few cases this led people to die like the Candace Newmaker incident. There's also a laundry list of spiritual types committing unethical acts because they believed it was the path to enlightenment. 

If you're suffering from psychosis, the absolute worst people you can involve yourself with are people that tell you the voices in your head are real and reaffirm the delusion. This doesn't just apply to spiritual healers, but many religious figures who believe the devil speaks to schizophrenics. The practitioners are far more dangerous than they realise, they hold an enormous amount of cognitive dissonance between the idea they're doing damage and their identity as "healers", and that blind spot makes them more dangerous than people give them credit for.

author: @jeffwozniak6674
text:
This is one of the worst interviews ever conducted by the vaunted bbc. The "newsreader" has repeated questions and observations that have been repeated by every other journalist since the heist happened. He hasn't mentioned where one suspect was going (Algeria), where the other was going (Mali), or that the DNA from the vest and helmet left behind contributed to the arrests, as has been reported on other news outlets (France24).
  Instead, he whips the same dead horse and asks if the jewels could be disassembled, melted down, recut, and sold on by now, continuing the same speculation ad infinitum for a week. He asks how valuable are the jewels (very), and how important a part of France's patrimony are they (a lot). He notes that they dropped and left behind the Bonaparte crown, a fact that led every story on the theft for a week. The interviewee's responses are equally as vague, predictable, and noncommittal. 
  Shame on you for your shoddy, lazy journalism.

text:
At about 5 P.M. two IDF jeeps suddenly swept into the village. The kids were still on the basketball court. The soldiers fired shots into the air to disperse the local residents and make them go home, the way you chase away stray dogs. Itâ€™s become routine: The army invades this village three times a week on average, usually at night. This time its troops showed up in daylight.

The streets emptied out. The kids playing soccer also scattered. Muhammad fled the schoolyard together with them and stood near the wall. The soldiers were in the valley below, some 250 meters away. They shouted and fired into the air. Immediately afterward one of them apparently knelt and shot Muhammad.

The soldiers then fired four tear-gas grenades at passersby, leaving Muhammad to bleed for three-four minutes before it was possible to evacuate him.

One of the boyâ€™s uncles, who lives nearby and saw what had happened, rushed out into the street and, together with his son, and carried Muhammad to the uncleâ€™s car. A video shows the uncle bundling his nephew, who seems to be lifeless, into the car. This week the uncle â€“ he is afraid to have his name published â€“ related that he found a pulse in the childâ€™s neck, albeit weak. He wanted to evacuate the boy to the government hospital in Yatta as fast as possible, but saw the same two jeeps heâ€™d seen in al-Rihiya driving slowly in front of him. He was afraid the soldiers would delay him and might also abduct Muhammad, so he chose a bypass road that doubled the time of the trip: 30 minutes instead of 15.

Another cousin, Aiham, 19, told us that he saw the moment at which Muhammad was hit, from the roof of his house. He related that the soldiers raised their arms in what looked to him like a gesture of triumph or joy. text:
Access


Topicsâ€ºTrade in the U.S.â€º
The Trump Administration's Trade Deals So Far
Trade Deals
by 
Katharina Buchholz,
 
Aug 4, 2025
On Wednesday, the latest trade deal of the U.S. with a foreign country to avoid high tariffs was announced. South Korea and the United States said that they only made an oral agreement due to time constraints lowering the Asian country's tariffs to 15 percent (from a threatened 25 percent), including on cars, and agreeing South Korea would invest in the U.S.

Previously, the United States and the European Union agreed on a deal that is lowering tariffs on European goods to 15 percent also. Taking into account exceptions, it is estimated that around 70 percent of EU imports to the U.S. will be affected by the new rate. The EU as part of the agreement is also investing an additional $600 billion in the U.S. and will purchase $750 billion worth of U.S. energy products. There has been no announcement of adjusted EU tariffs. As of the latest data, the EU only collects a levy on around a quarter of U.S. imports, the opposite of the new trade deal scenario, with the tariff rates on imports to the EU also lower.

Other deals struck with developed nations resemble the EU and South Korea agreements, showing two distinct themes for Trump's new trade deals that right now number only seven - a far cry from the dozens Trump announced should be closed before the August 4 deadline. Japan also agreed to big investments and purchases from the United States in exchange to a U.S. tariff rate lowered to 15 percent while keeping its import tariffs the same. A May deal also left the United Kingdom's import tariff rates intact while lowering U.S. tariffs on steel and aluminium to zero and carving out an exception for the import of 100,000 British cars at a rate of 10 percent. As the country never received a higher, so-called reciprocal tariff announcement from the Trump administration, its overall additional tariff is the globally announced 10 percent, which also remained unchanged.

While these seems like a lopsided agreements, so are other deals that the U.S. has struck with foreign countries to avert August tariff deadlines. The agreements with Asian nations Indonesia, Vietnam and the Philippines stipulate not only higher-than-before U.S. tariffs, but also nearly unlimited open-market access for U.S. products imported into these nations, something that has garnered heavy criticism in the countries affected.


Katharina Buchholz
Data Journalist
katharina.buchholz@statista.com

author: @GlobalWellBeing
text:
#FactsMatter Itâ€™s important to clarify the mechanics behind the government shutdown, beyond the political talking points. While House Minority Leader Hakeem Jeffries frames this as a â€œRepublican shutdown,â€ the reality is more complex. Even though Republicans currently control both the House and the Senate, reopening the government requires at least 60 votes in the Senate to overcome a filibuster. So far, Democrats have repeatedly blocked these measures.

This isnâ€™t about partisan blame in the abstractâ€”itâ€™s about real consequences for millions of Americans who are going without paychecks, food assistance, and other critical services. Framing this shutdown solely as a Republican failure misrepresents the procedural reality and obscures accountability. Acknowledging the full pictureâ€”where both chambersâ€™ rules and Democratic opposition have a direct impactâ€”is essential if we hope to address the human suffering caused by these delays.

Facts matter, and so does the well-being of the people affected.

author: @thefrequencypage
text:
Trumpâ€™s economic policies and authoritarian ambitions are not parallel tracks they are interwoven. 

The deliberate destabilization of the economy serves as both a smokescreen and a scaffold for autocratic consolidation. 

Recognizing this pattern is not alarmism; it is a necessary act of democratic vigilance.

The Engineered Collapse: 
How Trumpâ€™s 
Economic Sabotage 
Mirrors the Authoritarian Playbook

Donald Trumpâ€™s second-term trajectory reveals a pattern that aligns disturbingly well with the ten-point authoritarian strategy of deliberate economic destabilization. 

Far from being a byproduct of mismanagement, the economic distress under his leadership appears increasingly strategic an intentional dismantling of democratic guardrails to entrench personal power.

1. Systematic Middle-Class Erosion  

Trumpâ€™s tax policies and deregulation efforts have disproportionately benefited the ultra-wealthy while hollowing out the middle class. The 2017 tax cuts, extended and deepened in his second term, slashed corporate taxes and capital gains while offering minimal relief to wage earners.

Simultaneously, inflationary pressures exacerbated by trade wars and deregulated monopolies have eroded real wages, leaving middle-income Americans squeezed and politically disempowered.

2. Cultivating Economic Dependency  

By gutting federal agencies and redirecting relief funds through loyalty-based channels, Trump has fostered a system where access to aid is increasingly politicized. 

Emergency relief programs, especially during economic downturns and climate disasters, have been used to reward red states and punish blue ones, creating a dependency matrix that mirrors autocratic patronage systems.

3. Crony Capitalism Ascendant  

Independent businesses especially those in urban, progressive regions have been undermined by erratic tariffs, regulatory whiplash, and selective enforcement.

Meanwhile, Trump-aligned conglomerates and donors have received preferential treatment, from no-bid contracts to regulatory exemptions. 

This consolidates economic power within a loyalist elite, echoing the oligarchic structures of illiberal regimes.

4. Chaos as a Pretext for Control  

Economic instability has been weaponized to justify sweeping executive actions. 

Trumpâ€™s invocation of the Insurrection Act, threats to deploy the military domestically, and repeated suggestions of suspending elections or overriding state authority all follow the classic authoritarian script: create a crisis, then claim extraordinary powers to solve it.

5. Institutional Defunding and Delegitimization
  
Public universities, independent media, and scientific agencies have faced budget cuts, leadership purges, and smear campaigns. 

Trumpâ€™s attacks on the â€œfake news media,â€ the â€œdeep state,â€ and â€œradical leftâ€ academics serve to delegitimize dissent and dismantle the very institutions that uphold democratic accountability.

6. Scarcity as a Political Weapon  

From vaccine distribution to disaster aid, Trumpâ€™s administration has shown a willingness to withhold resources from political opponents. 

This tactic not only punishes dissent but also signals to the public that survival may depend on political loyalty a hallmark of authoritarian regimes.

7. Exhaustion as Suppression  

With inflation, housing insecurity, and healthcare costs spiraling, Americans are increasingly consumed by day-to-day survival.

This economic fatigue saps the energy needed for civic engagement, protest, or organizing creating a vacuum in which authoritarianism can flourish unchallenged.

8. Scapegoating and Nationalist Diversions
  
Trumpâ€™s rhetoric has consistently blamed immigrants, China, and â€œglobalist elitesâ€ for Americaâ€™s economic woes. 

This redirection of blame stokes xenophobia and nationalism, creating a siege mentality that justifies authoritarian crackdowns and distracts from domestic sabotage.

9. Corruption and Asset Seizure  

Economic downturns have enabled Trump-aligned interests to acquire distressed assets real estate, media outlets, and infrastructure at fire-sale prices. 

This mirrors kleptocratic regimes where economic collapse is a tool for wealth consolidation among the ruling class.

10. Electoral Manipulation via Economic Leverage  

Economic hardship has been used to suppress voter turnout, particularly in marginalized communities. 

Cuts to postal services, voter roll purges, and threats to withhold federal funds from states expanding mail-in voting all point to a strategy of economic coercion to undermine electoral competition.

author: @simonkapadia7582
text:
Quite a surface level analysis honestly, but then it's a video editorial so I suppose a comprehensive evaluation of the patterns and dynamics is unlikely. But the worldview and normative framework underlying it is quite stilted from the outset. After all, who says the 1970s involved a return to form or an improvement, rather than the beginning of a longer trajectory of decline that took time to manifest, which is a better reading of the evidence. This really is far closer to the 1930s, and I fear he completely fails to grasp the genuine systemic and cultural failures and how they coalesce.

 There's no question that some of the discontent with democracy is predicated on misinformation and identity politics, especially in Europe, but in the US the system really is deeply, irredeemably broken. Effective management isn't an option because it isn't possible, irrespective as to whether it would be sufficient on its own. Supreme court judgments have hamstrung legislative capacity to reform campaign finance, gun laws and other salient issues. The incentive structure around politics is so corrupt and corrosive that a race to the bottom is locked in, after all, the first to abandon gerrymandering simply loses harder. There is no incentive to fix anything in the US right now.

You could go on endlessly about it, trace it back to the founding. The practical reality is that the US system is broken, its people are impoverished and their lives are precarious. Its healthcare system is in a death spiral right now. It's not just 'faith in democracy', it's a collapsing system that was predicated on hegemonic dominance and which is now hollowed out, lacking infrastructure, investment and with a consumer base that cannot sustain itself. The US is in effect at the culmination of an arc of self-destructive neglect. It has only remained as wealthy as it is because of its power, and that is on the verge of collapsing now.

America will, in the end, have to rebuild itself, but it's too late to reform itself.

author: @WistfulBill
text:
Trust depends on validation. Facts are "real".   
The role of Morality is expressed in the Constitution as consensus.  Trust and Belief are objectively defined.
Who/what can be believed?  Simple and obvious.
There is an unrecognized corollary of freedom.  We are free to be ignorant.  No Human can understand everything.  We understand by focusing on one topic at a time, and we can learn by first-hand experience, as well as from the experiences of others.  We "trade" our time and ignorance for the knowledge of others, by trusting with whom we can believe.  We are free to select the authorities we trust.  There are two meanings in English for an "authority."  An authority of fact is not necessary an authority of appointment, and vice versa.   

An authority of fact is validated in each culture, and there are institutions who are trusted to validate authorities of facts.  For instance, if you need to repair the broken engine in your car, you have two choices: you can spend the time to learn about your engine, buying equipment and parts, and fixing it with your time and labor.  Because there is a market demand for fixing cars, there are experts that you can pay to fix your engine.  You know how to find the one you choose and can trade money you have earned with your time/expertise in exchange for the time/expertise.  You are likely to find that it is almost always advantageous to enlist an expert.  The authorized mechanic has experience, training and the resources earned through years of pursuing the disciplines of his topical expertise.  The same is true with nearly everything we do. You don't grow your own food.  You don't have to, because you can rely on the many experts who harvest food, ship it and present food for your trade. Facts are real.  There are no alternative facts, but there are in infinite number of false hypotheses.

Authorities can also be those who are assigned power by other authorities.  An authority of power may not be an authority of fact.  In fact, we are experiencing the assignment of power that are not backed by the knowledge and experience necessary to perform the job of being an assigned authority.  
If facts are denied and mythologies are used to replace facts, failure can be expected.  There have been a number of organized attacks on "science" in the past few decades.  The responsiveness of a free market depends on the growth of businesses in response to any market demand.  "Free enterprise" has been conflated as "capitalism".  Capitalism is a small part of free enterprise.  In fact, a rapidly growing service business needs little or no capital to then create its own capital from profits.  As businesses expand, they respond to market factors that threaten their institutions.  There are many ways to suppress innovation, and one powerful way is through the control of government regulation.  

If an authority is assigned to a job with no interest or expertise in that job, that is a fraud to those who are to benefit from that function. The US Constitution and the laws of Congress have progressively developed for centuries.  In the last two decades, the government that is designed to be "by the people" and "for the people" has become deliberately undermined.  The judicial branch has, with the Chevron decision, removed the expertise of science and replaced it with an impossible task for those with expertise in justice.  In less than a year, the sciences of health are no longer government policy, and the US will continue to experience increased morbidity and mortality.  The new administration appears to recognize that consequential increase in expenses and is divesting itself of any future fiscal responsibility.  The topic of insurance is used to conceal the actual issue of massive decline in the health of the US population.  That problem began in 2022, when a political movement attacked public health and killed over a million people since then.  Private insurance companies did not adjust insurance rates according to the expected expenses related to vaccination, so the overall cost of insurance was not associated with vaccination.  Those who did not get vaccinated were NOT faced with increased insurance rates.  Instead, the burden of the increased expenses were placed on all policy holders.  The customer of private insurances are not primarily those insured.  The actual customers are their employers who denied the need to take actions against the pandemic.  It could be argued that the pandemic could have been isolated and minimized by the political act of closing the US CDC laboratory in Wuhan, China, in 2016, that was there to be an early warning for the emergence of that kind of epidemic.  Now that mythological propagandists have replaced the scientific CDC, there can be no trust in the information provided by the CDC.

The US government is now in control by the insurrectionists who are enforcing their unilateral policies that are in violation of both the Constitution and congressional laws.  In fact, all internal fiscal transfers are no longer public because of their success in precipitating a "shut down".  Simultaneously, Congress has been closed for business, providing no public input of dialog and no oversight of the rogue decisions within the executive branch.  The Supreme Court has declared the tariffs by executive actions to be illegal but have allowed ICE to continue to collect them.  There is no accountability of the ICE employees or their use of the tariff money collected by them.  

Remedies:  Constitutional impeachment is no longer an option, because the perpetrators can't serve on the juries of their own crimes.  Many of the 147 Congressmen who voted to reject the 2020 electors, and to give the victory to candidate Trump on January 6, 2021 remain.  Mike Johnson, who proposed that bill has been rewarded with the position of Speaker of the House.  They believe that they have won their coup, and the people who devised that 2021 coup were paid by the Heritage Foundation to write Project 2025, which is now being implemented.  Project 2026 will follow, which is the "post-Constitutional" government that they will install after the "disestablishment" of the current government is completed.  Their goal is obviously to codify a system of "crony capitalism" to replace democracy.  In corporate terms, they overtly want to replace the role of a President as a Chief Operating Officer to a Chief Executive Officer, which is one of several changes that they can't install outside of their influence on the conspirators in the Supreme Court.  The problems aren't about "politics".  The problems that insure the downfall of the US success are all violations of the Constitution and laws... Criminal Corruption.  Many of the states remain unchanged, and the states, counties and cities have always been the institutions that fight the most crime.  They still have the resources and expertise to pursue justice for the criminals in the federal government.  Consequently, the current administration and the Heritage Foundation are attacking the state and local governments with the ICE (Immigration and Customs Enforcement), as well as state and federal armed forces.  If the enormous inefficiencies of corruption are not corrected, the US will collapse into the anarchy created by the loss of order, death and destruction that are inevitable.  The momentum of the economy is already manifested by turmoil and misappropriation of resources.  There appears to be no alternative to the execution of indictments and the incarceration of the criminals to prevent the continuation of this coup of 2021.  The DOJ, OLC, OMB and the Supreme Court have been corrupted, and citizens no longer have standing in federal courts.  When asked how Project 2025 would be implemented, a Heritage Foundation spokesman said that "the revolution will be bloodless, if the left allows."  Since that statement, it has become apparent that "the left" to them, means those opposing fascism: the Democrats, and moderates.  They are in opposition to the vast majority of "we, the people".   There are many civil servants who take their oath to the Constitution seriously.  They, and the majority of citizens, must remove the criminals from government.

Trumpâ€™s economic policies and authoritarian ambitions are not parallel tracks they are interwoven. 

The deliberate destabilization of the economy serves as both a smokescreen and a scaffold for autocratic consolidation. 

Recognizing this pattern is not alarmism; it is a necessary act of democratic vigilance.

The Engineered Collapse: 
How Trumpâ€™s 
Economic Sabotage 
Mirrors the Authoritarian Playbook

Donald Trumpâ€™s second-term trajectory reveals a pattern that aligns disturbingly well with the ten-point authoritarian strategy of deliberate economic destabilization. 

Far from being a byproduct of mismanagement, the economic distress under his leadership appears increasingly strategic an intentional dismantling of democratic guardrails to entrench personal power.

1. Systematic Middle-Class Erosion  

Trumpâ€™s tax policies and deregulation efforts have disproportionately benefited the ultra-wealthy while hollowing out the middle class. The 2017 tax cuts, extended and deepened in his second term, slashed corporate taxes and capital gains while offering minimal relief to wage earners.

Simultaneously, inflationary pressures exacerbated by trade wars and deregulated monopolies have eroded real wages, leaving middle-income Americans squeezed and politically disempowered.

2. Cultivating Economic Dependency  

By gutting federal agencies and redirecting relief funds through loyalty-based channels, Trump has fostered a system where access to aid is increasingly politicized. 

Emergency relief programs, especially during economic downturns and climate disasters, have been used to reward red states and punish blue ones, creating a dependency matrix that mirrors autocratic patronage systems.

3. Crony Capitalism Ascendant  

Independent businesses especially those in urban, progressive regions have been undermined by erratic tariffs, regulatory whiplash, and selective enforcement.

Meanwhile, Trump-aligned conglomerates and donors have received preferential treatment, from no-bid contracts to regulatory exemptions. 

This consolidates economic power within a loyalist elite, echoing the oligarchic structures of illiberal regimes.

4. Chaos as a Pretext for Control  

Economic instability has been weaponized to justify sweeping executive actions. 

Trumpâ€™s invocation of the Insurrection Act, threats to deploy the military domestically, and repeated suggestions of suspending elections or overriding state authority all follow the classic authoritarian script: create a crisis, then claim extraordinary powers to solve it.

5. Institutional Defunding and Delegitimization
  
Public universities, independent media, and scientific agencies have faced budget cuts, leadership purges, and smear campaigns. 

Trumpâ€™s attacks on the â€œfake news media,â€ the â€œdeep state,â€ and â€œradical leftâ€ academics serve to delegitimize dissent and dismantle the very institutions that uphold democratic accountability.

6. Scarcity as a Political Weapon  

From vaccine distribution to disaster aid, Trumpâ€™s administration has shown a willingness to withhold resources from political opponents. 

This tactic not only punishes dissent but also signals to the public that survival may depend on political loyalty a hallmark of authoritarian regimes.

7. Exhaustion as Suppression  

With inflation, housing insecurity, and healthcare costs spiraling, Americans are increasingly consumed by day-to-day survival.

This economic fatigue saps the energy needed for civic engagement, protest, or organizing creating a vacuum in which authoritarianism can flourish unchallenged.

8. Scapegoating and Nationalist Diversions
  
Trumpâ€™s rhetoric has consistently blamed immigrants, China, and â€œglobalist elitesâ€ for Americaâ€™s economic woes. 

This redirection of blame stokes xenophobia and nationalism, creating a siege mentality that justifies authoritarian crackdowns and distracts from domestic sabotage.

9. Corruption and Asset Seizure  

Economic downturns have enabled Trump-aligned interests to acquire distressed assets real estate, media outlets, and infrastructure at fire-sale prices. 

This mirrors kleptocratic regimes where economic collapse is a tool for wealth consolidation among the ruling class.

10. Electoral Manipulation via Economic Leverage  

Economic hardship has been used to suppress voter turnout, particularly in marginalized communities. 

Cuts to postal services, voter roll purges, and threats to withhold federal funds from states expanding mail-in voting all point to a strategy of economic coercion to undermine electoral competition.

author: @thefrequencypage
text:
Trumpâ€™s economic policies and authoritarian ambitions are not parallel tracks they are interwoven. 

The deliberate destabilization of the economy serves as both a smokescreen and a scaffold for autocratic consolidation. 

Recognizing this pattern is not alarmism; it is a necessary act of democratic vigilance.

The Engineered Collapse: 
How Trumpâ€™s 
Economic Sabotage 
Mirrors the Authoritarian Playbook

Donald Trumpâ€™s second-term trajectory reveals a pattern that aligns disturbingly well with the ten-point authoritarian strategy of deliberate economic destabilization. 

Far from being a byproduct of mismanagement, the economic distress under his leadership appears increasingly strategic an intentional dismantling of democratic guardrails to entrench personal power.

1. Systematic Middle-Class Erosion  

Trumpâ€™s tax policies and deregulation efforts have disproportionately benefited the ultra-wealthy while hollowing out the middle class. The 2017 tax cuts, extended and deepened in his second term, slashed corporate taxes and capital gains while offering minimal relief to wage earners.

Simultaneously, inflationary pressures exacerbated by trade wars and deregulated monopolies have eroded real wages, leaving middle-income Americans squeezed and politically disempowered.

2. Cultivating Economic Dependency  

By gutting federal agencies and redirecting relief funds through loyalty-based channels, Trump has fostered a system where access to aid is increasingly politicized. 

Emergency relief programs, especially during economic downturns and climate disasters, have been used to reward red states and punish blue ones, creating a dependency matrix that mirrors autocratic patronage systems.

3. Crony Capitalism Ascendant  

Independent businesses especially those in urban, progressive regions have been undermined by erratic tariffs, regulatory whiplash, and selective enforcement.

Meanwhile, Trump-aligned conglomerates and donors have received preferential treatment, from no-bid contracts to regulatory exemptions. 

This consolidates economic power within a loyalist elite, echoing the oligarchic structures of illiberal regimes.

4. Chaos as a Pretext for Control  

Economic instability has been weaponized to justify sweeping executive actions. 

Trumpâ€™s invocation of the Insurrection Act, threats to deploy the military domestically, and repeated suggestions of suspending elections or overriding state authority all follow the classic authoritarian script: create a crisis, then claim extraordinary powers to solve it.

5. Institutional Defunding and Delegitimization
  
Public universities, independent media, and scientific agencies have faced budget cuts, leadership purges, and smear campaigns. 

Trumpâ€™s attacks on the â€œfake news media,â€ the â€œdeep state,â€ and â€œradical leftâ€ academics serve to delegitimize dissent and dismantle the very institutions that uphold democratic accountability.

6. Scarcity as a Political Weapon  

From vaccine distribution to disaster aid, Trumpâ€™s administration has shown a willingness to withhold resources from political opponents. 

This tactic not only punishes dissent but also signals to the public that survival may depend on political loyalty a hallmark of authoritarian regimes.

7. Exhaustion as Suppression  

With inflation, housing insecurity, and healthcare costs spiraling, Americans are increasingly consumed by day-to-day survival.

This economic fatigue saps the energy needed for civic engagement, protest, or organizing creating a vacuum in which authoritarianism can flourish unchallenged.

8. Scapegoating and Nationalist Diversions
  
Trumpâ€™s rhetoric has consistently blamed immigrants, China, and â€œglobalist elitesâ€ for Americaâ€™s economic woes. 

This redirection of blame stokes xenophobia and nationalism, creating a siege mentality that justifies authoritarian crackdowns and distracts from domestic sabotage.

9. Corruption and Asset Seizure  

Economic downturns have enabled Trump-aligned interests to acquire distressed assets real estate, media outlets, and infrastructure at fire-sale prices. 

This mirrors kleptocratic regimes where economic collapse is a tool for wealth consolidation among the ruling class.

10. Electoral Manipulation via Economic Leverage  

Economic hardship has been used to suppress voter turnout, particularly in marginalized communities. 

Cuts to postal services, voter roll purges, and threats to withhold federal funds from states expanding mail-in voting all point to a strategy of economic coercion to undermine electoral competition.

author: @RalfOltmanns
text:
Arnie is quite naive on this matter. But he's got one good point: Let's do re-districting in ALL states by an indepentent team of experts.
Take the population of a state, divide that number by a factor (i. e. 50,000 or 100,000 or a reasonable factor, because i. e. California has a way larger population than Montana), then start in the northwest of each state and draw districts with that number of inhabitant. The districts should be as even as possible, not creative shapes. Continue with districts from West to East and start again in the next row in the West.
The areas of those districts will be different, but the population per district should be as even as possible, give or take a few permille.

text:
From the Gospel according to Luke
12:39-48

Jesus said to his disciples:
"Be sure of this:
if the master of the house had known the hour
when the thief was coming,
he would not have let his house be broken into.
You also must be prepared,
for at an hour you do not expect, the Son of Man will come."

Then Peter said,
"Lord, is this parable meant for us or for everyone?"
And the Lord replied,
"Who, then, is the faithful and prudent steward
whom the master will put in charge of his servants
to distribute the food allowance at the proper time?
Blessed is that servant whom his master on arrival finds doing so.
Truly, I say to you, he will put him
in charge of all his property.
But if that servant says to himself,
'My master is delayed in coming,'
and begins to beat the menservants and the maidservants,
to eat and drink and get drunk,
then that servant's master will come
on an unexpected day and at an unknown hour
and will punish the servant severely
and assign him a place with the unfaithful.
That servant who knew his master's will
but did not make preparations nor act in accord with his will
shall be beaten severely;
and the servant who was ignorant of his master's will
but acted in a way deserving of a severe beating
shall be beaten only lightly.
Much will be required of the person entrusted with much,
and still more will be demanded of the person entrusted with more

text: My eyes have opened, I'll never see a parking spot the way same again. Hearing you two plan the stages felt more like planning moves on a chess board rather than playing car-parkour. Still, the most impressive part of the day has to be Kronii's playlist. If those tunes ever see the light of day more than one therapist is getting kicked to the curb. Maybe the magic was in the journey, maybe you had to left all the rage there on the road to find the true peace at the end. Beautiful if you think about it

                                       dahlah.

Isn't it already become a habit

maybe this is the right time
to set them all free
no need to ask 'why' anymore

if the truth is
you don't keep getting the right answer
don't cry about it, just keep trying to solve (end) the puzzle

because at the end of the day
you are way stronger than you thought you'd be

Just 'dahlah'
Oh just 'dahlah'
go with the flow

Just 'dahlah'

go with the flow

mau gimana lagi (id: it is what it is)

and went above and makes you feel powerless
and all your effort just feels in vain 

if the truth is
you don't keep getting the right answer
don't cry about it, just keep trying to solve (end) the puzzle

Just let it go,
because at the end of the day
you are way stronger than you thought you'd be

release all the control (limiter)
push the gas to it's maximum and go!
take the L and end it there!

if the truth is
you don't get the answer
don't cry about it, just keep trying to solve (end) the puzzle

Just let it go,
because at the end of the day
you are way stronger than you thought you'd be
you are way stronger than you thought you'd be


Just 'dahlah'
Oh just 'dahlah'
go with the flow

go with the flow

author: @lowliethxd1471
text:
I've been feeeling existential dread these days due to things not going as I planned it to be, both in work and personal life. (intensive workload, not meeting deadlines,  little to no sleep, failing my recent graduate review test) 

Whenever I make a plan to "control" the directions I want to take,  it feels like the world is conspiring to set me away from it everytime. 

The frustration just gets worse and heavier the longer it last. And made me feel down, dissatissfied and useless

This song blew all that feeling.

The entire song was the thing I needed to hear. And the second part is my favorite because it really tugged on my personally. 

Apologies for the trauma dump, but what what I wanted to say is  thank you, for letting me here this.
(Auto saved so I can play it whenever)
